tial?9.129 In brief, ductal NaC1 absorption proceeds as follows. Na passively enters the cell from the ductai lumen through amiloride-sensitive Na channels at the luminal membrane and is pumped out across the basal membrane in exchange for K (Fig. 20). Cellular K leaks out passively through K channels, generating a membrane potential.59 K then recycles, being pumped in, in exchange for cellular Na. C1 follows passively down the gradient through C1 channels at both the luminal and basolateral membranes and across intercellular junctions (paraceilular pathways). In addition to NaC1 absorption, the sweat duct also may absorb HCO3 either directly or via H ion secretion?4 As discussed earlier, the capacity for the duct to absorb NaC1 is limited so that sweat NaC1 concentration increases with increasing sweat flow rate (Fig. 16). The overall regulatory mechanism of ductal absorption function is still poorly understood.
